          "body": "Having announced the coming king, Balaam turns to four rapid oracles against surrounding nations. Amalek — Israel's first military enemy after the exodus (Exodus 17:8-16) and the paradigm of relentless anti-Israel hostility — is given the briefest and most final verdict: 'his end shall be destruction' (24:20). The Kenites, despite their apparently secure cliff-dwellings, will be carried captive by Asshur (24:21-22). Then comes the most historically enigmatic of the four (24:23-24): ships from Kittim afflict Asshur and Eber, and they also come to destruction. Kittim's identification has exercised interpreters from Jerome to the present: Cyprus is the most literal reading; Alexander's Macedonian fleet, or Rome, are later interpretive expansions attested in Daniel 11:30 and 1QM. What is theologically stable across all identifications is the oracle's logic: even the power that temporarily overcomes Asshur will itself perish. No empire endures. The cumulative effect of 24:20-24 is to place every human political structure — Amalek, the Kenites, Asshur, Kittim — under the same eschatological verdict the chapter opened with: 'who can live except God has ordained it?' (24:23). Only the king from Jacob endures."
